    "id": "how-much-money-do-i-actually-need-to-start-dropshipping",
    "slug": "how-much-money-do-i-actually-need-to-start-dropshipping",
    "question": "How much money do I actually need to start dropshipping properly?",
    "answerHTML": "\n<div class=\"faq-origin-tag\">The real answer nobody gives beginners — most courses are vague on this deliberately</div>\n<p>The real number depends on your testing strategy. Here's the honest breakdown:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Absolute minimum (undercapitalized, high risk) — $500–$300 total:</strong> Gets you one lean product test ($300–400 in ad spend), Shopify ($1/month trial then $39/month), domain ($12), and 1–2 months of tools. At this budget, a single test failure wipes you out. You have no margin for iteration.</li>\n<li><strong>Functional minimum (1–2 serious tests) — $1,500–$2,000:</strong> Gives you room for 2 product tests ($500–700 each with proper creative volume), basic tools, and a month of Shopify. Most beginners who get their first sale are in this range.</li>\n<li><strong>Realistic starting budget (5+ tests, proper volume) — $3,000–$5,000:</strong> Allows you to test 5–10 products properly, iterate on winners, and build a basic creative library without going broke after 2 failures. This is what operators who hit their first winning product before quitting typically had.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Below $500: don't run paid ads.</strong> Start with organic TikTok, build creative skills (see Module 01), and save until you have enough to test properly. Running underfunded paid ads wastes money and teaches you nothing useful.</p>\n<div class=\"et-nudge\" style=\"margin:16px 0 4px;\">\n<div class=\"et-nudge-icon\">🚀</div>\n<div class=\"et-nudge-text\">\n<div class=\"et-nudge-label\">Below $500 right now?</div>\n<div class=\"et-nudge-title\">The income path that builds toward your store</div>\n<p class=\"et-nudge-desc\">EcomTalent teaches ecommerce skills brands actively hire for — at $97/month, one freelance client covers the cost and then some. Build capital while learning the exact skills you'll use when you launch.</p>\n</div>\n<a class=\"et-nudge-btn\" href=\"https://whop.com/ecomtalent/ecomtalent?a=internetjames\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">See EcomTalent →</a>\n</div>\n<div class=\"faq-tactical-box\"><strong>Tactical Fix</strong>Calculate your break-even ROAS before spending a dollar. Know your per-test budget (not your total budget). Never put more than 30% of your total capital into one product test. Keep a cash reserve — Shopify payouts are net-14 to net-30. You'll need float.</div>\n",
    "answerText": "The real number depends on your testing strategy. Here's the honest breakdown: Absolute minimum (undercapitalized, high risk) — $500–$300 total: Gets you one lean product test ($300–400 in ad spend), Shopify ($1/month trial then $39/month), domain ($12), and 1–2 months of tools. At this budget, a single test failure wipes you out. You have no margin for iteration. Functional minimum (1–2 serious tests) — $1,500–$2,000: Gives you room for 2 product tests ($500–700 each with proper creative volume), basic tools, and a month of Shopify. Most beginners who get their first sale are in this range. Realistic starting budget (5+ tests, proper volume) — $3,000–$5,000: Allows you to test 5–10 products properly, iterate on winners, and build a basic creative library without going broke after 2 failures. This is what operators who hit their first winning product before quitting typically had. Below $500: don't run paid ads. Start with organic TikTok, build creative skills (see Module 01), and save until you have enough to test properly. Running underfunded paid ads wastes money and teaches you nothing useful. 🚀 Below $500 right now? The income path that builds toward your store EcomTalent teaches ecommerce skills brands actively hire for — at $97/month, one freelance client covers the cost and then some. Build capital while learning the exact skills you'll use when you launch. See EcomTalent → Tactical FixCalculate your break-even ROAS before spending a dollar. Know your per-test budget (not your total budget). Never put more than 30% of your total capital into one product test. Keep a cash reserve — Shopify payouts are net-14 to net-30. You'll need float.",
    "category": "Cash Flow & Budget",
